Greetings!

I am tracking down a bug that appears to be related to mt76 / mt7921e
kernel modules and/or relevant mediatek firmware / hardware.

---------------------------------------------
1. Description of the problem
---------------------------------------------
Wifi part of the network card seems to go unresponsive. Neither connection
attempts nor scan attempts work. `iw dev scan` returns either nothing or -19
busy.
Firmware is not crashing, driver remains responsive.

---------------------------------------------
2. Steps to Reproduce
---------------------------------------------
Any of the following actions can trigger the issue:
- Boot
- Reboot
- Wake from suspend
- Wake from hibernation
- mt7921e kernel module reload
- chip_reset via /sys/kernel/debug

There is a 5-10% chance after each to enter the failstate.
On some networks failstate occurs a lot more often than others. Cause 
remains
undetermined. No correlation to network settings or signal strength has been
found thus far.

Alternatively the issue may occur when there's an AP-side disconnection.

---------------------------------------------
3. Environment and Hardware
---------------------------------------------
Laptop: Acer Aspire 5 A517-52-542X
Network Card: MEDIATEK Corp. MT7921 802.11ax PCI Express Wireless 
Network Adapter
OS: Alt Linux Education P11 (Also reproduced on Alt Linux Education 
Sisyphus)
Driver: mt7921e
Kernel: Linux version 6.12.61-6.12-alt1
(builder@localhost.localdomain) (gcc-13 (GCC) 13.2.1 20240128
(ALT Sisyphus 13.2.1-alt3), GNU ld (GNU Binutils) 2.41.0.20230826)
#1 SMP PREEMPT_DYNAMIC Thu Dec 11 13:04:56 UTC 2025
Firmware: 2025-10-11

Also reproduced on ASUS VivoBook S14 OLED (same network card), however vast
majority of testing was conducted on the Acer.

---------------------------------------------
4. Failstate details
---------------------------------------------
Comparison of data from `/sys/kernel/debug/ieee80211/phyX/mt76/`:
- tmac values of VHT80, VHT160, HE996 seem abnormally high in failed state
(40-54)
- Much lower number of low power wakes, BAs in failed state

Full outputs of `cat /sys/kernel/debug/ieee80211/phyX/my76/*` for 
successful and
failed cases are attached.

---------------------------------------------
5. Narrowing down the problem
---------------------------------------------
- Connecting using NetworkManager with wpa_supplicant backend triggers 
the bug.
- Connecting using iw does not trigger the bug.
- Connecting using wpa_supplicant does not trigger the bug.
- Connecting using iwd does not trigger the bug.
- Connecting using NetworkManager with iwd backend triggers the bug.
- Network Manager service being active triggers the bug even if the
connection itself is performed using wpa_supplicant.
- Connecting using NetworkManager with delayed start of the latter by 6 
seconds
still triggers the bug.

---------------------------------------------
6. Attempted Fixes
---------------------------------------------
Fixes partially sourced from older similiar bug reports and distribution 
support
threads dated anywhere from 2022 to 2026.

Tested Kernel Options
- pcie_aspm=off
- mt7921e.disable_aspm=0
- mt7921-common.disable_clc=0
- pci=noaer
- pcie_port_pm=off
- iommu=soft
- iommu=pt
- pm_async=off
- acpi_sleep=nobl
- pci=nomsi
- pci=nommconf
- mem_sleep_default=deep
- processor.max_cstate=1
- idle=poll
- pci=realloc
- pcie_port_pm=off

Tested with Kernel Versions
- 6.12.34
- 6.12.61
- 6.18.20
- 6.19.10
- 7.0-rc1

Tested with Firmware Versions
- 2025-08-08
- 2026-02-21
- 2025-06-07
- Built from latest commit as of 26.02.2026
- With reverted commit ba4183 as per a solution from a similiar bug

Bug occurs independent of
- ACPI errors
- PM failing to restore -110
Bug occurs even if neither is present.

Changing network parameters
- Security (or lack thereof)
- Frequency
- Signal strength

Changing NetworkManager Parameters
- Power saving
- MAC randomization
- pmf

Disabling hardware offloading
Disabling packet queue
Disabling bluetooth part of the network card
Disabling Wake-on-WLAN BIOS setting

---------------------------------------------
7. Attachments
---------------------------------------------
I have collected both successful case logs and failed case logs where 
applicable
for cross-reference purposes.

I am attaching dmesg, journalctl and traces as links to github gists because
they are too large.
Successful case:
https://gist.github.com/silverducks143/89c7d27b696a8e968b813ba1baa3d92e
Failed case:
https://gist.github.com/silverducks143/90c104d77217df9306c17854a607e322

Attached <state>_kernel_debug.txt files contain output of
`cat /sys/kernel/debug/ieee80211/phyX/mt76/*`

I am also attaching a script that can be used to reproduce the issue:
nm-test-supplicant.sh
This script simply cycles the kernel module until a failstate occurs.
It expects a saved network with automatic connection enabled in NM.
I am happy to conduct any necessary testing myself as well.

---------------------------------------------
Let me know if any further information or testing is required.
Thank you for your time.

